<h1>
When Cancer Leaves <span>Molecular Clues</span>
</h1>

<p>
Cancer does not begin as a visible disease. It begins as biological disruption — changes in DNA, gene activity, proteins, metabolism, lipids, epigenetic regulation, immunity, and the surrounding cellular environment.
</p>
<div class="hero-image">

  <img

    src="/cancer-molecular-clues-hero-v1.png"

    alt="Cancer Molecular Clues Multi-omics Story"

  >

</div>
<div class="story-panel">

<p>
A person may feel healthy while molecular changes are already unfolding inside tissues. A cell may acquire genetic alterations. Regulatory systems may become unstable. Proteins may signal growth at the wrong time. Metabolism may shift. Inflammation may reshape the local environment.
</p>

<p>
Omics sciences help researchers study these hidden molecular patterns. Instead of looking at one layer alone, omics approaches allow scientists to examine biology as an interconnected system.
</p>

<p>
This is why cancer research increasingly depends on multi-layer molecular interpretation: not only asking whether disease is present, but asking how disease begins, how it changes over time, and why it responds differently across individuals.
</p>

</div>

